# Brief: Hearth & Crumb Provisions — fresh-thread thesis memo (v1)

This is the v1 brief for a **fresh** memo thread: no prior version, no
external dossier, no diligence pack. The drafter is producing the first
defensible take on whether Hearth & Crumb is a plausible pre-seed bet,
working from the originating idea seed plus general knowledge of the
small-batch CPG category.

The job of v1 is **to resolve the recommendation target**, not to defend a
predetermined one. The default `recommendation_target: undecided` is
load-bearing: by the end of v1 the memo should land on invest / pass /
conditional with named conditions, and the path it took to get there should
be auditable in the Evidence section.

## What the memo must establish (load-bearing questions)

The v1 reviewer should be able to check each of these off the memo body. If
any is missing or hand-waved, dim 3 (Constraint satisfaction) and dim 4
(Evidence quality) will score down.

- [ ] **What category is this, really?** Specialty bakery, shelf-stable
      pantry, frozen, or DTC subscription? The unit economics fork hard on
      this — name the category before reasoning about it.
- [ ] **Who is the customer, and how often do they buy?** Repeat rate is
      the single most decision-relevant number for small-batch CPG at this
      stage. State the assumed cohort and the assumed cadence explicitly.
- [ ] **What is the unit margin at current batch size, and what does it
      become at the next plausible batch size?** If the founder can't get to
      ~40% gross at the next step-up, the venture is structurally hard.
- [ ] **What is the distribution wedge?** DTC, farmer's market, regional
      grocery, food-service — pick one as the v1 wedge and defend why it's
      the *right* one to win first. ("All of the above" is not a wedge.)
- [ ] **What kills it?** Name the single most likely failure mode (most
      common for this category: capacity ceiling at the kitchen, COGS
      shock from a key ingredient, or founder-burnout from production
      labor). The Risks section should lead with this one.
- [ ] **What would a pass look like?** Even if v1 ends on invest, the memo
      should explicitly state what evidence would have flipped it to pass.
      This is what makes the recommendation falsifiable.

## Source material

This is the **fresh** case, so source material is intentionally light. The
drafter should NOT invent a "read order" section — there is no prior version
to thread through. The available inputs are:

- The originating row in `IDEAS.md` / `VENTURES.md` (the venture name, the
  one-line thesis, the founder reference if any).
- General knowledge of the specialty-food category: typical gross margins,
  shelf-life economics, the DTC → wholesale transition pattern, the role of
  copacking, the standard FDA labeling regime.
- Any public material on the company (a Squarespace shop, an Instagram
  presence, a single press mention) — cite these explicitly when used.

No `refs/` directory is expected for v1. If diligence material lands later
(a founder deck, a financial model, a tasting-panel result), it goes in
`refs/` and gets cited in v2's brief, not retro-fitted here.

## Hard rules for v1

These are non-negotiable constraints the drafter MUST satisfy. Violations
should be flagged as critical by the reviewer.

- **No invented financials.** If the brief doesn't supply a number and the
  drafter can't anchor it to a category benchmark (with citation), the
  memo says so explicitly rather than fabricating. "Assume ~40% gross at
  scale, typical for the category" is fine; a fictional P&L table is not.
- **No invented customer evidence.** Don't write "100 repeat customers
  surveyed" if no survey exists. State what would be needed to make the
  thesis non-speculative, and put that in the Risks / Open questions
  section.
- **Recommendation must be falsifiable.** Whatever the recommendation
  lands on, the memo must state the specific evidence that would have
  flipped it. If v1 cannot construct a falsifiable thesis from the
  available material, that itself is the recommendation: *pass for
  now, revisit on these specific signals*.

## Out of scope for v1

These are deliberately deferred. The reviewer should NOT down-score the
memo for omitting them — but if v1 silently expands into them, dim 7
(Scope discipline) will score down.

- Cap table / dilution modeling. There's no term sheet yet.
- Detailed competitive teardown of every regional specialty bakery. A
  three-actor framing (the closest direct comp, the closest adjacency,
  the "if they nailed scale, what would they look like" lookalike) is
  sufficient for v1.
- Founder reference calls. Plan to gate v2 on at least one founder
  reference if v1 lands on invest or conditional.
- Detailed go-to-market plan. v1 picks the wedge; v2 details the play.

## What v2 might tighten

A forward-planning placeholder so the reader (and the next reviser) knows
where the thread is heading. Items here are NOT promises — they're the
most likely next-version edits.

- If v1 lands on **invest** or **conditional**: add one founder reference,
  one channel-economics deep-dive (whichever wedge v1 picked), and a
  named-condition list (what specifically would need to be true at v3 to
  release the check).
- If v1 lands on **pass**: tighten the "what would flip this" section
  into a watch-list with named triggers (e.g. "revisit if DTC repeat
  rate clears 35% at $40 AOV").
- Either way, expect v2 to compress: v1 is the exploratory pass, v2 is
  the disciplined pass. Target length will narrow accordingly via the
  document's `target_length_overrides` map on `<project>/BRIEF.md`.
